span=4 |''[[Kangsi Coming]]''\n| rowspan=4 |[[Best Host in a Variety Programme(Golden Bell Awards)|Best Host in a Variety Programme]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2006\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2007\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2008\n| {{nom}}\n{{end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|3872617}}\n* {{in lang|zh}} [http://t.sina.com.cn/dees Dee Hsu's Sina Microblog]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hsu, Dee}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Taipei]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese television personalities]]\n[[Category:21st-century Taiwanese actresses]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGolden Bell Awards:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dee_Hsu"}
{"title_page": "SD Victoria", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=''SD Victoria''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image               = \n| Ship caption             = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header              =\n| Ship country             = [[United Kingdom]]\n| Ship flag                = [[File:Civil Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg|70px]]\n| Ship name                = ''SD Victoria''\n| Ship owner               =\n| Ship namesake            = [[Queen Victoria]]\n| Ship ordered             =\n| Ship builder             =\n| Ship laid down           =\n| Ship launched            = 2010\n| Ship acquired            =\n| Ship commissioned        =\n| Ship decommissioned      =\n| Ship in service          = 25 May 2010\n| Ship out of service      =\n| Ship struck              =\n| Ship reinstated          =\n| Ship homeport            = \n| Ship identification      = *{{IMO Number|9534107}}\n*{{MMSI Number|235068802}}\n*[[Maritime call sign|Callsign]]: 2BRX2\n| Ship honours             =\n| Ship fate                =\n| Ship status              = Active\n| Ship notes               =\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header              =\n| Header caption           =\n| Ship class               = Worldwide support ship\n| Ship tonnage             = 3,522 [[Gross tonnage|GT]]<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n| Ship displacement        =\n| Ship length              = {{convert|83|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n| Ship beam                = {{convert|16|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n| Ship draught             = {{convert|4.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n| Ship draft               =\n| Ship propulsion          = Two Caterpillar 3516B diesels driving two shafts with controllable pitch propellers\n| Ship speed               = {{convert|14|kn|abbr=on|lk=in}}<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n| Ship range               =\n| Ship complement          = 16 crew (accommodation for up to 72)<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n| Ship sensors             =\n| Ship EW                  =\n| Ship armament            =\n| Ship armour              =\n| Ship armor               =\n| Ship aircraft            =\n| Ship aircraft facilities =*Helicopter winching deck\n| Ship notes               =*Flat work deck\n*Cranes\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''SD Victoria''''' is a worldwide support ship operated by [[Serco Marine Services]] in support of the United Kingdom's [[Naval Service (United Kingdom)|Naval Service]], and currently the second largest ship operated by Serco Marine Services, after [[SD Northern River|SD ''Northern River'']].<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\">{{cite book|last=Bush|first=Steve|title=British Warships and Auxiliaries|year=2014|publisher=Maritime Books|page=75 |isbn=1904459552}}</ref>\n\nHer duties involve supporting training operations and transporting military personnel and equipment around the world. ''SD Victoria'' has also been photographed<ref>https://www.marinetraffic.com/en/photos/of/ships/shipid:194330/#forward</ref> carrying [[List of active Royal Marines military watercraft#Specialist Craft|Specialist Craft]] operated by the [[Special Boat Service]].<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n\nOn board, ''SD Victoria'' is equipped with several operations and briefing rooms.<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Naval Service (United Kingdom)]]\n*[[List of ships of Serco Marine Services]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sercomarine.com/Images/SD%20Victoria_tcm29-38291.pdf Serco Marine ''SD Victoria''] (sercomarine.com)\n*[https://www.marinetraffic.com/en/ais/details/ships/shipid:194330/mmsi:235068802/imo:9534107/vessel:SD_VICTORIA \"Vessel Tracking\"] (MarineTraffic.com)\n\n{{-}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:SD Victoria}}\n[[Category:Serco Marine Services (ships)|Victoria]]\n[[Category:2010 ships]]\n\n{{UK-aux-ship-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=SD ''Victoria''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image               = \n| Ship caption             = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header              =\n| Ship country             = [[United Kingdom]]\n| Ship flag                = [[File:Civil Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg|70px]]\n| Ship name                = ''SD Victoria''\n| Ship owner               =\n| Ship namesake            = [[Queen Victoria]]\n| Ship ordered             =\n| Ship builder             =\n| Ship laid down           =\n| Ship launched            = 2010\n| Ship acquired            =\n| Ship commissioned        =\n| Ship decommissioned      =\n| Ship in service          = 25 May 2010\n| Ship out of service      =\n| Ship struck              =\n| Ship reinstated          =\n| Ship homeport            = \n| Ship identification      = *{{IMO Number|9534107}}\n*{{MMSI Number|235068802}}\n*[[Maritime call sign|Callsign]]: 2BRX2\n| Ship honours             =\n| Ship fate                =\n| Ship status              = Active\n| Ship notes               =\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header              =\n| Header caption           =\n| Ship class               = Worldwide support ship\n| Ship tonnage             = 3,522 [[Gross tonnage|GT]]<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n| Ship displacement        =\n| Ship length              = {{convert|83|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n| Ship beam                = {{convert|16|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n| Ship draught             = {{convert|4.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n| Ship draft               =\n| Ship propulsion          = Two Caterpillar 3516B diesels driving two shafts with controllable pitch propellers\n| Ship speed               = {{convert|14|kn|abbr=on|lk=in}}<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n| Ship range               =\n| Ship complement          = 16 crew (accommodation for up to 72)<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n| Ship sensors             =\n| Ship EW                  =\n| Ship armament            =\n| Ship armour              =\n| Ship armor               =\n| Ship aircraft            =\n| Ship aircraft facilities =*Helicopter winching deck\n| Ship notes               =*Flat work deck\n*Cranes\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''SD Victoria''''' is a worldwide support ship operated by [[Serco Marine Services]] in support of the United Kingdom's [[Naval Service (United Kingdom)|Naval Service]], and currently the second largest ship operated by Serco Marine Services, after [[SD Northern River|SD ''Northern River'']].<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\">{{cite book|last=Bush|first=Steve|title=British Warships and Auxiliaries|year=2014|publisher=Maritime Books|page=75 |isbn=1904459552}}</ref>\n\nHer duties involve supporting training operations and transporting military personnel and equipment around the world. ''SD Victoria'' has also been photographed<ref>https://www.marinetraffic.com/en/photos/of/ships/shipid:194330/#forward</ref> carrying [[List of active Royal Marines military watercraft#Specialist Craft|Specialist Craft]] operated by the [[Special Boat Service]].<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n\nOn board, ''SD Victoria'' is equipped with several operations and briefing rooms.<ref name=\"Steve Bush 2014\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Naval Service (United Kingdom)]]\n*[[List of ships of Serco Marine Services]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sercomarine.com/Images/SD%20Victoria_tcm29-38291.pdf Serco Marine ''SD Victoria''] (sercomarine.com)\n*[https://www.marinetraffic.com/en/ais/details/ships/shipid:194330/mmsi:235068802/imo:9534107/vessel:SD_VICTORIA \"Vessel Tracking\"] (MarineTraffic.com)\n\n{{-}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:SD Victoria}}\n[[Category:Serco Marine Services (ships)|Victoria]]\n[[Category:2010 ships]]\n\n{{UK-aux-ship-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lyndaship", "label": "safe", "comment": "displaytitle", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SD_Victoria"}
{"title_page": "Tongai Mnangagwa", "text_new": "<ref name=\":2\" /><br />\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Tongai Mnangagwa\n| office = [[House of Assembly (Zimbabwe)|Member of the Parliament of Zimbabwe]]<br />for [[Harare South]]\n| predecessor = [[Shadreck Mashayamombe]]\n| termstart = 5 September 2018\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1978|02|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Zambia]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Gwendolyn Lina Mnangagwa|2001}}\n| children = 5\n\nJeremy Leon,\n\nJamie Leona,\n\nJeminah Tanatswa,\n\nJayden Tongai,\n\nJamila Reign Tadiswa\n\n| alma_mater = [[Harare Polytechnic]], [[ZOU]]\n| residence = [[Harare]], [[Zimbabwe]]\n| party = [[ZANU\u2013PF]]\n}}\n\n'''Tongai Mafidi Mnangagwa''' (born 10 February 1978) is a [[Zimbabwe]]an politician who currently serves as the [[House of Assembly (Zimbabwe)|Member of Parliament]] for the [[Harare South]] he is the sole [[ZANU\u2013PF]] MP representing [[Harare Province]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMnangagwa was born on 10 February 1978 in [[Zambia]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.parlzim.gov.zw/component/k2/hon-mnangagwa-tongai|title=Hon. Mnangagwa Tongai|last=|first=|date=|website=Parliament of Zimbabwe|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He moved to [[Zimbabwe]] as a young child, attending Haig Park Primary School in [[Harare]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He did his [[GCE Ordinary Level|O Levels]] at [[Gokomere High School]], a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[boarding school]] in [[Masvingo Province]], before completing his [[secondary education]] at [[Prince Edward School]], a [[State school|government]] [[Secondary school|high school]] in Harare.<ref name=\":0\" /> He then attended [[Harare Polytechnic]], where he earned a [[Academic certificate|certificate]] in [[marketing]].<ref name=\":0\" /> currently studying for Bachelor of science honors in development studies at Zimbabwe Open University.\n\n== Political career ==\nMnangagwa joined [[ZANU\u2013PF]] at age 18, and became the youth chairperson for the party's Tangwena District at age 20.<ref name=\":0\" /> Later, he moved to [[Harare South]] and joined the party's Leopold Takawira District as a committee member, later rising to become the [[political commissar]] of the main board.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2018, Mnangagwa was ZANU\u2013PF's candidate for the House of Assembly in the 2018, running against over a dozen other candidates.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.zbc.co.zw/2018-elections-national-assembly-results/|title=2018 Elections: National Assembly Results|last=|first=|date=|website=ZBC News|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-30}}</ref> On election day, Mnangagwa won with a 39% [[Plurality (voting)|plurality]], defeating the two [[MDC Alliance]] candidates, [[incumbent]] [[Shadreck Mashayamombe]], and Tichaona Saurombe, who received 24% and 12%, respectively, as well as the [[Movement for Democratic Change \u2013 Tsvangirai|MDC\u2013T]] candidate, [[Desmond Jambaya]], who earned 6% of the vote.<ref name=\":1\" /> He was sworn into Parliament on 5 September 2018.\n\n== Personal life ==\nMnangagwa is married and lives in the [[Mabelreign, Harare|Harare south]] suburb of Harare.<ref name=\":0\" /> He has five children with his wife, Gwendolyn Mnangagwa.\n\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |[[2018 Zimbabwean general election|2018 election]], [[Harare South]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Candidate\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{ZANU-PF/meta/color}}\" |\n|'''Tongai Mnangagwa'''\n|[[ZANU\u2013PF]]\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |24,503\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |39.3\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Movement for Democratic Change/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Shadreck Mashayamombe]]\n|[[MDC Alliance]]\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |21,363\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |34.3\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Movement for Democratic Change/meta/color}}\" |\n|Tichaona Saurombe\n|[[MDC Alliance]]\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |7,868\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |12.6\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Movement for Democratic Change/meta/color}}\" |\n|Desmond Jambaya\n|[[Movement for Democratic Change \u2013 Tsvangirai|MDC\u2013T]]\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |4,016\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |6.4\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Independent/meta/color}}\" |\n|Robson Kazetete\n|[[Independent politician|Independent]]\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |1,829\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |2.9\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#2B3B90 |\n|Tatenda Chigwada\n|[[People's Rainbow Coalition|PRC]]\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |679\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |1.1\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#000000 |\n|Spencer Chiwanika\n|[[National Patriotic Front (Zimbabwe)|NPF]]\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |620\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |1.0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Independent/meta/color}}\" |\n|Elliot Piki\n|Independent\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |393\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |0.6\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Independent/meta/color}}\" |\n|Nathan Nyambuya\n|Independent\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |325\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |0.5\n|-\n|\n|Hearvy Ndagurwa\n|[[Zimbabwe Partnership for Prosperity|ZIPP]]\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |189\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |0.3\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Independent/meta/color}}\" |\n|Maxwell Munondo\n|Independent\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |151\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |0.2\n|-\n|\n|Gaylord Kurisa\n|Build Zim Alliance\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |150\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |0.2\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#95C322 |\n|Runwork Mharadze\n|[[National Constitutional Assembly|NCA]]\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |142\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |0.2\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Independent/meta/color}}\" |\n|Super Tanyiswa\n|Independent\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |136\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |0.2\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:right\" |'''Total'''\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |62,364\n| style=\"text-align:right\" |\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:left\" |Source:<ref name=\":1\" />\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of members of the 9th Parliament of Zimbabwe]]\n\n== References ==\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mnangagwa, Tongai}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Zimbabwean politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Zimbabwean politicians]]\n[[Category:Harare Polytechnic alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Assembly (Zimbabwe)]]\n[[Category:People from Harare]]\n[[Category:Zambian emigrants to Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:ZANU\u2013PF politicians]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "<ref name=\":2\" /><br />\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Tongai Mnangagwa\n| office = [[House of Assembly (Zimbabwe)|Member of the Parliament of Zimbabwe]]<br />for [[Harare South]]\n| predecessor = [[Shadreck Mashayamombe]]\n| termstart = 5 September 2018\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1978|02|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Zambia]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Gwendolyn Lina Mnangagwa|2001}}\n| children = 5\n\nJeremy Leon,\n\nJamie Leona,\n\nJeminah Tanatswa,\n\nJayden Tongai,\n\nJamila Reign Tadiswa\n\n| alma_mater = [[Harare Polytechnic]], [[ZOU]]\n| residence = [[Harare]], [[Zimbabwe]]\n| party = [[ZANU\u2013PF]]\n}}\n\n'''Tongai Mafidi Mnangagwa''' (born 10 February 1978) is a [[Zimbabwe]]an politician who currently serves as the [[House of Assembly (Zimbabwe)|Member of Parliament]] for the [[Harare South]] he is the sole [[ZANU\u2013PF]] MP representing [[Harare Province]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMnangagwa was born on 10 February 1978 in [[Zambia]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.parlzim.gov.zw/component/k2/hon-mnangagwa-tongai|title=Hon. Mnangagwa Tongai|last=|first=|date=|website=Parliament of Zimbabwe|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He moved to [[Zimbabwe]] as a young child, attending Haig Park Primary School in [[Harare]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He did his [[GCE Ordinary Level|O Levels]] at [[Gokomere High School]], a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[boarding school]] in [[Masvingo Province]], before completing his [[secondary education]] at [[Prince Edward School]], a [[State school|government]] [[Secondary school|high school]] in Harare.<ref name=\":0\" /> He then attended [[Harare Polytechnic]], where he earned a [[Academic certificate|certificate]] in [[marketing]].<ref name=\":0\" /> currently studying for Bachelor of science honors in development studies at Zimbabwe Open University.\n\n== Political career ==\nMnangagwa joined [[ZANU\u2013PF]] at age 18, and became the youth chairperson for the party's Tangwena District at age 20.<ref name=\":0\" /> Later, he moved to [[Harare South]] and joined the party's Leopold Takawira District as a committee member, later rising to become the [[political commissar]] of the main board.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2018, Mnangagwa was ZANU\u2013PF's candidate for the House of Assembly in the 2018, running against over a dozen other candidates.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.zbc.co.zw/2018-elections-national-assembly-results/|title=2018 Elections: National Assembly Results|last=|first=|date=|website=ZBC News|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-30}}</ref> On election day, Mnangagwa won with a 39% [[Plurality (voting)|plurality]], defeating the two [[MDC Alliance]] candidates, [[incumbent]] [[Shadreck Mashayamombe]], and Tichaona Saurombe, who received 24% and 12%, respectively, as well as the [[Movement for Democratic Change \u2013 Tsvangirai|MDC\u2013T]] candidate, [[Desmond Jambaya]], who earned 6% of the vote.<ref name=\":1\" /> He was sworn into Parliament on 5 September 2018.\n\n== Personal life ==\nMnangagwa is married and lives in the [[Mabelreign, Harare|Harare south]] suburb of Harare.<ref name=\":0\" /> He has five children with his wife, Gwendolyn Mnangagwa.<ref name=\":2\">\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| 